# Testing Guidelines

## Test File Structure

Follow the pattern from [Counter.test.tsx](mdc:src/components/Counter.test.tsx):

```typescript
import { describe, it, expect, beforeEach } from 'vitest'
import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react'
import userEvent from '@testing-library/user-event'
import ComponentName from './ComponentName'

describe('ComponentName', () => {
  beforeEach(() => {
    // Setup before each test
  })

  it('should render correctly', () => {
    render(<ComponentName />)
    // Assertions
  })
})
```

## Testing Patterns

### Rendering Tests
```typescript
it('renders the component', () => {
  render(<ComponentName title="Test" />)
  expect(screen.getByText('Test')).toBeInTheDocument()
})
```

### User Interaction Tests
```typescript
it('handles button click', async () => {
  const user = userEvent.setup()
  const handleClick = vi.fn()
  
  render(<Button onClick={handleClick}>Click me</Button>)
  
  await user.click(screen.getByRole('button'))
  expect(handleClick).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1)
})
```

### State Management Tests
```typescript
it('updates store on action', () => {
  const { getState } = useStore
  
  render(<Component />)
  fireEvent.click(screen.getByRole('button'))
  
  expect(getState().count).toBe(1)
})
```

### Form Testing
```typescript
it('submits form with correct data', async () => {
  const user = userEvent.setup()
  const onSubmit = vi.fn()
  
  render(<Form onSubmit={onSubmit} />)
  
  await user.type(screen.getByLabelText('Email'), 'test@example.com')
  await user.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /submit/i }))
  
  expect(onSubmit).toHaveBeenCalledWith({ email: 'test@example.com' })
})
```

## What to Test

### Must Test
- Component renders without errors
- User interactions (clicks, form submissions)
- Conditional rendering (loading, error, empty states)
- Props are applied correctly
- State changes trigger re-renders

### Should Test
- Accessibility (keyboard navigation, ARIA attributes)
- Edge cases (empty arrays, null values, boundary conditions)
- Integration with stores (Zustand)
- Responsive behavior (if critical)

### Don't Test
- Implementation details (internal state, private methods)
- Third-party library functionality
- Styling (unless critical for functionality)
- Trivial code (simple getters/setters)

## Testing Utilities

### Custom Render Function
```typescript
// src/test/utils.tsx
import { render } from '@testing-library/react'
import { ReactElement } from 'react'

function customRender(ui: ReactElement, options = {}) {
  return render(ui, {
    // Add providers, context, etc.
    ...options,
  })
}

export * from '@testing-library/react'
export { customRender as render }
```

### Mock Data
```typescript
// src/test/mocks.ts
export const mockUser = {
  id: '1',
  name: 'John Doe',
  email: 'john@example.com',
}
```

## Test Organization

- One test file per component
- Group related tests with `describe` blocks
- Use descriptive test names: `'should increment count when button is clicked'`
- Keep tests independent (use `beforeEach` for setup)
- Clean up after tests (handled by `afterEach` in [setup.ts](mdc:src/test/setup.ts))

## Coverage Goals

- Aim for 80%+ coverage on critical components
- Focus on user-facing functionality
- Don't obsess over 100% coverage
